You said:
Uncaught Command get_db_path not found in console
ChatGPT said:

The error:

nginx
Uncaught Command get_db_path not found

means your Rust backend does NOT define a Tauri command named get_db_path, but your JS code is calling:

js
await invoke("get_db_path")

So Tauri says: There is NO such command.

Lets fix it.

1. Add the get_db_path command in Rust

Edit src-tauri/src/main.rs:

rust
#![cfg_attr(not(debug_assertions), windows_subsystem = "windows")]

use tauri::{Manager, command};
use tauri_plugin_opener::OpenerExt;
use tauri_plugin_sql::Builder as SqlBuilder;

#[command]
fn get_db_path(app_handle: tauri::AppHandle) -> String {
    let path = app_handle
        .path()
        .app_data_dir()
        .expect("cannot get app data dir");

    // Example: <AppData>/yourapp/all.db
    let db_path = path.join("all.db");

    db_path.to_string_lossy().to_string()
}

fn main() {
    tauri::Builder::default()
        .plugin(SqlBuilder::default().build())
        .plugin(tauri_plugin_opener::init())

        // REGISTER COMMAND HERE
        .invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![get_db_path])

        .run(tauri::generate_context!())
        .expect("error while running tauri application");
}

2. JS side stays the same:

js
const dbPath = await invoke("get_db_path");
const db = await Database.load(`sqlite:${dbPath}`);

Explanation

Tauri v2 requires:

1. Rust function must be annotated with #[command]

2. Must be included in:

rust
.invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![get_db_path])

Without that, JS cannot call the function.

(Optional) Ensure the DB file exists

Add this to get_db_path:

rust
if !db_path.exists() {
    std::fs::create_dir_all(db_path.parent().unwrap()).ok();
    std::fs::File::create(&db_path).ok();
}

You said:
Error tauri.conf.json error: Additional properties are not allowed ('permissions' was unexpected)
ChatGPT said:

You're using Tauri v2, and in Tauri v2 there is NO root-level "permissions" field.
Thats why you get:

java
Additional properties are not allowed ('permissions' was unexpected)

In Tauri v2, ALL permissions must be inside a capability, not at the root.

Correct way to enable SQL in Tauri v2

You must create a custom capability file for SQL, inside:

pgsql
src-tauri/capabilities/sql.json

You CANNOT put SQL permissions inside tauri.conf.json.
You MUST place them in a separate file under the capabilities folder.

STEP 1 Create capability file

Create:

pgsql
src-tauri/capabilities/sql.json

Put this inside:

json
{
  "$schema": "https://schema.tauri.app/config/2",
  "identifier": "sql-capability",
  "description": "Allows SQLite plugin DB loading",
  "permissions": {
    "sql": {
      "allow-load": ["*"],
      "default": true
    }
  }
}

STEP 2 Tell Tauri to use that capability

In your tauri.conf.json add inside:

json
"app": {
  "security": {
    "csp": null,
    "capabilities": [
      "window-controls",
      "sql-capability"     <-- ADD THIS
    ]
  }
}

Your file will look like:

json
"security": {
  "csp": null,
  "capabilities": [
    "window-controls",
    "sql-capability"
  ]
}

Do NOT put SQL permissions inside tauri.conf.json
Only list the capability name here.

After this:

Restart:

nginx
npx tauri dev

And Database.load() will finally succeed.

Why this works

In Tauri v2:

  • Root-level "permissions" is removed

  • You must declare permissions inside capability files

  • tauri.conf.json only references them

ChatGPT said:

Ah now this is a Tauri v2 JSON capabilities parsing error:

pgsql
failed to parse JSON: invalid type: map, expected a sequence at line 11 column 1

This happens because capability JSON files must be an array, or a properly structured object Tauri expects. Most likely, your sql.json (or window-controls.json) has the wrong structure.

Correct sql.json for Tauri v2

Create src-tauri/capabilities/sql.json:

json
{
  "$schema": "https://schema.tauri.app/config/2",
  "identifier": "sql-capability",
  "permissions": [
    {
      "sql": {
        "allow-load": ["*"],
        "default": true
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key points:

  1. "permissions" must be an array of objects, not a single object.

  2. Each permission object defines a plugin and its settings.

  3. Do not include anything else like windows or local in the SQL capability.

Correct window-controls.json

Similarly, src-tauri/capabilities/window-controls.json:

json
{
  "$schema": "https://schema.tauri.app/config/2",
  "identifier": "window-controls",
  "description": "Allows controlling window (min/max/close)",
  "permissions": [
    "core:default",
    "core:window:allow-close",
    "core:window:allow-minimize",
    "core:window:allow-maximize",
    "core:window:allow-unmaximize",
    "core:window:allow-toggle-maximize"
  ]
}

tauri.conf.json "security" section

Reference them like this:

json
"security": {
  "csp": null,
  "capabilities": [
    "window-controls",
    "sql-capability"
  ]
